<tr><td colspan=2><ul>
<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0><tr><td>
	     <table class=mform  border=0 cellpadding=1 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
	     <form action=/cgi-bin/mrate.pl name=f100101077752906>
	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=classes2.html?class=12&mid=100101077752906>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=classes2.html?class=12&mid=100101077752906>RE: Earth pet issue</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes2.html?class=12&mid=100101077752906#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Thu, Sep 20th 2:32 PM 2001</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span><br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default [2.00]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>I must agree with Zura.&nbsp;&nbsp;It's been a long time since I played the lower end game, and at 55, I still get alot of good use out of my earth pet.  When raiding in places like the hole, you don't want a pet around at all with the horrid pathing, but when we get too many adds, I help the enchanters with CC using my earth pet.  As you go higher in levels, and you decide you want to fight in the nastier zones (like Sirens Grotto) against the harder mobs that will eat you alive, you're going to need your earth pet.  He has the most HP and will last longer then any other.  My earth pets root also does damage and after I malice, it will usually stick the mobs fairly well.  For someone who isn't used to chain casting pets, the root is very important in holding the mob off while you get your other pet up and attacking.  The worst pet in the game IMO is the post 49 fire pet.  I haven the spell, and I've played with it a few times, and I have to say that the post 49 fire pet is most definately the worst pet of all.</p>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
